Carolina, you know, this one is called one must learn to love. And I feel like if this isn't what

00:57:18.340 --> 00:57:24.560
the classroom, I, I, if this is what I see the classroom as doing, and, and I'm pretty sure this

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:31.060
is the way y'all see that your classroom is doing as well. This happens to us in music. First, one must

00:57:31.060 --> 00:57:36.580
learn to hear a figure and melody at all, to detect and distinguish it, to isolate and delimit it

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:44.240
as, uh, as a life in itself. Then one needs effort and goodwill to stand it despite its strangeness.

00:57:44.740 --> 00:57:48.600
Patience with its appearance and expression and kind heartedness about its oddity.

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:54.200
Finally comes a moment when we are used to it, when we expect it, when we sense that we'd miss it if

00:57:54.200 --> 00:58:00.820
it were missing. And now it continues relent, uh, can, now it continues relentlessly to compel and

00:58:00.820 --> 00:58:06.300
and enchant us until we have become its humble and enraptured lovers who no longer want

00:58:06.300 --> 00:58:12.620
anything better from the world than it and it again. But this happens to us, not only in music,

00:58:12.620 --> 00:58:18.060
it is just in just this way that we have learned to love everything we now love. We are always

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:24.200
rewarded in the end for our goodwill, our patience, our fair-mindedness and gentleness with what is

00:58:24.200 --> 00:58:30.140
strange as it gradually casts off its veil and presents itself as a new indescribable beauty.

00:58:30.640 --> 00:58:36.960
That is its thanks for our hospitality. Even he who loves himself will have learned it this way.

00:58:36.960 --> 00:59:06.940
If that's not a pedagogy of difference, I don't, I don't know what is this, this sort of repetition of, of, of, of, of generosity and, and patience that is for the sake of allowing something else to emerge. And by the way, you know, I would add or wrinkle in there and allow for yourself to reemerge in relationship to it as well. That you're not going to be.

00:59:06.940 --> 00:59:16.900
You're not this, you know, stable sort of paternalistic. This isn't a paternalistic kind of love wherein I, you know, I have the dominant position and then just allows this otherwise nascent thing.

00:59:16.900 --> 00:59:29.160
Quite the opposite, right? Like quite the opposite in this case. It's like it requires patience, fair-mindedness and gentleness with what is strange in order for that to shed its veil and turn into something new and of indescribable beauty.

00:59:29.160 --> 00:59:42.820
That is the way it thanks us for our hospitality, right? Like in other words, we have to be capable of welcoming. We have to be capable of welcoming and, and that's learning to love, right? To, to, you know, not just accept, right?

00:59:42.820 --> 00:59:54.620
Not just tolerate, you know, I mean, that's, that's a step. Acceptance and tolerance are a step, but learning to love that, which is not, that is not I, you know, that is not me.

00:59:54.620 --> 01:00:08.860
My only hesitation around, cause I completely, this is how I try to conduct myself in the classroom. It's like generous readings of my students writing of the conversation in general. I try to be as receptive as possible, not just to appropriate what they're saying.

01:00:08.960 --> 01:00:25.000
I try to be open to alterity, but I'm not sure that, I mean, I don't know. I, I feel like I'm doing a pretty good job practically speaking, but just theoretically, you don't know the motivations of your conduct or behavior all the time.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:42.420
So is this a matter of just willing that, that relation to alterity or trying? Is it like an attempt? Is it a perpetual attempt? Or like, how do you think about it? Because for me, there's a little bit of a disconnect, at least conceptually speaking.

01:00:42.420 --> 01:01:00.420
It has to be a continuous attempt. Like you certainly can't know it ahead of time. And I would also say that it can't, because, you know, as, as John said, it's not tolerance or acceptance that there has to be, there, there's a back and forthness to it too, that sometimes, you know, patience and generousness and all these other sorts of things are not, it's not simply openness.

01:01:00.420 --> 01:01:27.160
It's not a passivity. Sometimes there needs to be like a challenging, sometimes there needs to be, you know, some, something else that sort of like provoke response. But it's always sort of like a, I mean, this is where it's experimental for me is it's, it's try something and then see how it responds and then adapt to it. And, and, you know, to go back to like, and allow yourself to be changed by the thing that that's coming back to you.

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:54.180
So the sort of experimental, I think that's, I mean, that's, it's the best way that I can think of it too, boo boo, because, because I will say, yeah, there is a kind of will to it, right? There is a kind of a commitment to this, but the commitment is not a resolute one. The commitment is one of, I'm going to try and see how this plays. I thought as an example, when Nathaniel was speaking there, I thought of your prospectus defense and you remember how mad I was at you.

01:01:54.880 --> 01:02:23.440
And I said it, right? Like I said it in the thing. I'm like, in the defense, I'm like, this document has made me angry. And I'm going to explain to you, I'm going to explain to you why it has made me angry, because I think it's really important. And, and it's, and that expression of anger was like, that was a form of caring. Right? That was, it was, that was not, because I certainly know in myself, like, if I didn't give a shit, I'd be like, well, fuck it, who cares? You know, is that was a form of care.

01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:42.580
Now, there are many ways that that thing could have gone. And who knows? And I would, it's incumbent upon me in that situation, if I am willing and encounter with alterity, to be receptive to how it plays for you. At the same time, I'm only me. I am not an assortment of all possible things.

01:02:42.960 --> 01:02:56.120
And so there are things that I'm not going to do. I'm not going to be like the nice, gentle, I'm just not going to be that guy. You know, like, oh, no, anything that you say is really smart and really good. And it's like, no, sometimes it's stupid. And sometimes you're wrong.

01:02:57.420 --> 01:03:08.320
And, but that's, it's not good or, it's not better or worse. It's just different. They're just different things. And you as a different kind of organism are going to respond differently to some things.

01:03:09.360 --> 01:03:17.340
But I'm wondering, like, in a situation like that, if that was a calculate, like, a calculated risk you took, like, I'm sure he'll be able to handle it.

01:03:17.560 --> 01:03:17.880
Absolutely.

01:03:18.040 --> 01:03:21.840
Like, would you have done that with somebody else in the same exact way?

01:03:22.540 --> 01:03:26.440
Well, I mean, I certainly have done it with other people in similar ways.

01:03:26.620 --> 01:03:27.480
No, I know.

01:03:27.600 --> 01:03:29.140
But not everybody else. I would say that.

01:03:29.400 --> 01:03:30.820
Yeah, certain people you wouldn't do it.

01:03:30.820 --> 01:03:32.760
Absolutely. Absolutely not.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:35.160
Like, there, you know, I learned very much.

01:03:35.500 --> 01:03:47.520
I mean, that's to me the great thing about graduate pedagogy that's, at least for me, different from undergraduate pedagogy is we have a long enough period of time that different types of interactions can occur.

01:03:47.520 --> 01:04:03.820
It's years. It's not weeks. And the result of that is different things that, for instance, if I discovered, and this has happened to me before, that that kind of exchange makes you shut down, then I don't do that anymore, you know.

01:04:03.940 --> 01:04:09.700
Now, again, I'm not all things to all people, so I am limited in my array of possible behaviors.

01:04:09.700 --> 01:04:24.440
But, like, that, like, okay, you try some, like, I interact, obviously, with different students differently, you know, and I'm really nice to some students, which is, people find shocking sometimes, you know.

01:04:24.540 --> 01:04:24.700
Yeah.

01:04:24.900 --> 01:04:31.820
And people find, you know, I've told you the story of the friend of mine who got, like, when I said, hey, this paper is really great, she's like, you're done with me.

01:04:31.880 --> 01:04:32.820
You hate me now, right?

01:04:33.080 --> 01:04:35.740
I was like, no, no, no, it actually really is great.

01:04:36.280 --> 01:04:40.120
You're like, no, this is your dismissive, this is how you're dismissive, you're being complimentary.

01:04:40.540 --> 01:04:42.200
And you're like, no, no, I liked it, you know.

01:04:43.280 --> 01:04:50.220
So, you know, but I do think that there is a kind of, I don't know, it's a responsibility to me.

01:04:50.340 --> 01:04:54.220
And that's, the responsibility comes from, that's the fun part of being alive.

01:04:54.600 --> 01:04:57.580
Like, that's, so the responsibility is not one, it's not a weight.

01:04:57.960 --> 01:05:11.040
It's like, here's what opens the world to you, is learning how to encounter it as something other than just another version of you, or a failed version of you, or an inadequate version of you, or an idealized version of you.

01:05:11.720 --> 01:05:25.940
You know, it's like, I think it's really, for instance, I think about the number of times, I mean, I've been studying and immersed in the English language for 54 years, well, whenever I started talking, but like for, you know, my entire life, right?

01:05:26.460 --> 01:05:29.240
And I frequently have misunderstandings with people.

01:05:29.240 --> 01:05:37.920
And I will say, almost to, in every, almost in every case, not in every case, because some of them, but I thoroughly enjoy those misunderstandings.

01:05:38.080 --> 01:05:44.680
I find them fucking fascinating when I realize, oh my gosh, I see how you heard that thing that I said that way.

01:05:44.840 --> 01:05:47.220
I didn't think of it that way, and I didn't mean it that way.

01:05:47.300 --> 01:05:49.780
But the way that you heard it, it's, you're not wrong.

01:05:50.600 --> 01:05:51.280
Makes sense.

01:05:51.480 --> 01:05:51.620
Yeah.

01:05:51.920 --> 01:05:52.220
Right?

01:05:52.340 --> 01:05:56.000
And I'm like, what happens to me in that moment is I've encountered another.

01:05:57.020 --> 01:06:00.720
And it's like, and it's like, wow, that is really cool.

01:06:01.120 --> 01:06:01.440
Like, so.

01:06:01.680 --> 01:06:03.080
And it's making it a delight.

01:06:03.720 --> 01:06:08.920
Yeah, that sense of responsibility is not a weight, it's a fascination, you know, at least for me.

01:06:09.020 --> 01:06:13.880
And that's, the teaching, man, like, what is teaching other than that, you know?

01:06:13.920 --> 01:06:18.560
It's not getting them to be mini-me's, because fuck, nobody wants that.

01:06:19.580 --> 01:06:20.780
I don't want a little.

01:06:21.060 --> 01:06:22.300
Well, some of them did, I guess.

01:06:22.300 --> 01:06:29.020
Well, I think, in fact, a lot of teachers, yes, I think a lot of teachers, for a lot of teachers, it is, because you could say the same thing about me.

01:06:29.020 --> 01:06:36.520
Well, John, you are trying to make them into mini-me's, insofar as the me there is supposed to be this adaptable comportment in relation to others.

01:06:36.580 --> 01:06:37.600
I'm like, yeah, okay, you're right.

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:37.960
You win.

01:06:38.020 --> 01:06:39.200
On a logic scale, you win.

01:06:39.820 --> 01:06:40.020
Right?

01:06:40.220 --> 01:06:41.380
You're right.

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:43.780
I am trying to reproduce versions of myself.

01:06:44.320 --> 01:06:45.300
But myself, in that case, isn't the content.

01:06:45.300 --> 01:06:50.920
Insofar as myself is a self-differentiating, perpetually becoming, yes.

01:06:50.920 --> 01:06:51.480
That's right.

01:06:51.480 --> 01:06:59.220
With the notion that any mini-me that you sort of create, given enough time, it's going to be completely unrecognizable to both yourself and themself.

01:06:59.220 --> 01:07:00.500
Little mini-others.

01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:01.840
One would hope, right?

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:02.880
One would hope.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:05.140
I mean, look, you got, you know, I don't know.

01:07:05.200 --> 01:07:09.440
I mean, like, I feel very close to you guys, but you guys are not me, and I'm cool with that.

01:07:09.520 --> 01:07:11.900
Like, I'm not only cool with that, like, it's necessary.

01:07:12.060 --> 01:07:12.700
It's important.

01:07:12.880 --> 01:07:12.980
Yeah.

01:07:13.320 --> 01:07:13.920
I don't want you.

01:07:13.920 --> 01:07:15.040
It'd be a boring conversation, otherwise.

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:16.520
It wouldn't be a conversation.

01:07:16.660 --> 01:07:17.920
It would be a monologue, right?

01:07:17.920 --> 01:07:23.660
So here's the end of 339, Vita Femina, or Femina.

01:07:24.200 --> 01:07:33.240
I mean to say that the world is brimming with beautiful things, but nevertheless poor, very poor, in beautiful moments, and in the unveilings of those things.

01:07:33.680 --> 01:07:36.700
But perhaps that is the strongest magic of life.

01:07:36.700 --> 01:07:45.700
It is covered by a veil of beautiful possibilities, woven with the threads of gold, promising, resisting, bashful, mocking, compassionate, and seductive.

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:47.620
Yes, life is a woman.

01:07:47.620 --> 01:07:48.340
Life is a woman.

01:07:49.040 --> 01:07:49.740
Oh, no.

01:07:49.940 --> 01:07:52.860
It's like, everything was really great up to that last sentence.

01:07:52.860 --> 01:07:53.220
I know, I know, I know.

01:07:53.600 --> 01:07:56.460
Actually, I thought about not reading the last line.

01:07:56.580 --> 01:07:57.360
I know, I know.

01:07:57.540 --> 01:07:58.120
But it gives you that.

01:07:58.120 --> 01:07:59.160
I didn't even get to that shit.

01:07:59.340 --> 01:08:00.820
It's the beyond good Nemo, right?

01:08:00.960 --> 01:08:02.520
Like, he's supposing to be a woman.

01:08:02.740 --> 01:08:02.800
Yeah, it's true.

01:08:02.800 --> 01:08:03.420
You know, like, it's.

01:08:03.980 --> 01:08:05.320
I think it's some pretty simple thing.

01:08:05.400 --> 01:08:06.440
It's just ways, like, what?

01:08:06.480 --> 01:08:08.220
Because life's way better than being a man.

01:08:08.680 --> 01:08:09.280
I know.

01:08:09.720 --> 01:08:10.740
I actually think that.

01:08:10.740 --> 01:08:13.580
It's like, life would suck if I was like a man.

01:08:13.960 --> 01:08:14.320
Yes.

01:08:14.900 --> 01:08:15.260
Yeah.

01:08:16.140 --> 01:08:16.500
Yeah.

01:08:17.320 --> 01:08:18.360
It's just hard.

01:08:18.360 --> 01:08:20.480
It kind of sounds like a Rolling Stones lyric or something.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:23.020
Life is a woman.

01:08:23.280 --> 01:08:24.020
Yeah, it does.

01:08:24.140 --> 01:08:24.800
It really does.

01:08:25.080 --> 01:08:25.460
And it sounds.

01:08:25.600 --> 01:08:25.700
Yeah.

01:08:25.760 --> 01:08:30.640
And I recognize all of the ways in which that can be an incredibly patriarchal, condescending

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:31.500
thing to say.

01:08:31.880 --> 01:08:35.400
Like, and I recognize all the ways in which it can be heard that way as well.

01:08:35.780 --> 01:08:37.280
But I mean, that's just like, no.

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:38.360
Here's the deal.

01:08:38.360 --> 01:08:41.000
Life is dissimulation and uncertainty.

01:08:41.580 --> 01:08:48.280
And if you treat it with sort of, if you encounter it with patience and interest and fascination,

01:08:48.440 --> 01:08:52.300
it will reward you with, you know, you'll be fascinated.

01:08:52.460 --> 01:08:54.920
Like, with otherness, right?

01:08:54.920 --> 01:09:09.740
Like, and so, yes, the sort of, I don't know, synecdochal reduction of life as a woman is one that's hard to hear anymore for pretty understandable reasons.

01:09:09.740 --> 01:09:13.300
Sorry, this is a little tangential, but related to what you're saying.

01:09:13.460 --> 01:09:22.420
I mean, Nietzsche, as we all know, or at least as the three of us know, was sick for, and I think we talked about this, was like perpetually sick and ill.

01:09:23.140 --> 01:09:27.060
And I think Bataille, I was reading some Bataille who was obsessed with Nietzsche.

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:33.040
And he was basically just highlighting the fact that all of the things were going wrong for this guy.

01:09:33.160 --> 01:09:43.920
Like, he could have been a symptom of those things, but he chose to sort of overcome them and enact this, whatever, like laughter in that sense.

01:09:44.280 --> 01:09:52.120
As opposed to, like, in relation to other people who are given all of the affordances and still lapse into whatever Christian judgment,

01:09:52.380 --> 01:09:59.360
Nietzsche somehow, with all the excuses, was still able to do this other thing, which is just kind of astonishing.

01:09:59.360 --> 01:10:01.180
He could have been a dark, cynical guy.

01:10:02.620 --> 01:10:06.080
And it's so funny that he's sort of, like, often configured as that.

01:10:06.080 --> 01:10:08.400
I know, like, Nietzsche as nihilist.

01:10:08.520 --> 01:10:10.020
It's like, eh, you got nihilism.

01:10:10.300 --> 01:10:12.000
You clearly didn't read any of this.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:12.900
I know, I know.

01:10:12.980 --> 01:10:17.660
The dark brooding, the dark brooding, like, I've always said, like, in a Hollywood movie,

01:10:17.700 --> 01:10:21.940
if you want to have a teenager who's dark and brooding, you have him reading Nietzsche at some point, you know,

01:10:22.040 --> 01:10:24.260
and you're like, that's just not in it at all.

01:10:24.260 --> 01:10:28.920
Do you think that's residue of him being appropriated by the Nazis?

01:10:29.460 --> 01:10:31.180
I think it's the God is dead thing.

01:10:31.480 --> 01:10:33.020
I think it's God is dead.

01:10:33.020 --> 01:10:34.200
Just that statement.

01:10:34.520 --> 01:10:34.720
Yeah.

01:10:35.940 --> 01:10:38.560
But then he also has what doesn't kill you makes you stronger.

01:10:38.720 --> 01:10:41.620
There's not, you know, that's a huge fucking cultural.

01:10:41.620 --> 01:10:43.940
I mean, he's the thinker of affirmation.

01:10:44.120 --> 01:10:49.660
But, you know, I will also say, like, I remember when I was reading Nietzsche when I was a teenager,

01:10:49.660 --> 01:11:03.080
and I very much had the punk rock, kick ass, break shit, fuck the idols, it wasn't sounding out the idols, you know, it was, let's smash them all, let's fuck up conventional values like that.

01:11:03.740 --> 01:11:04.880
You know, I very much had that.

01:11:04.880 --> 01:11:08.460
And I still have, I still harbor a deep sympathy for that as well.

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:18.360
But you think of the passages that Nathaniel has just read there, they're very gentle, you know, and they do have that sense of like, oh, an interest in beauty and love.

01:11:18.400 --> 01:11:21.240
These are not words that you usually associate with Nietzsche.

01:11:21.680 --> 01:11:25.660
And they have a very particular resonance in Nietzsche for that reason.

01:11:26.660 --> 01:11:35.160
And so the Nietzsche that appeals to me now and has for the last 20 years is very much a different Nietzsche than the one that, like, initially got me interested.

01:11:36.220 --> 01:11:38.720
I almost forgot about the nihilism Nietzsche.

01:11:38.980 --> 01:11:43.240
Because what we read, like, with Deleuze's Nietzsche, I was reading Batai's Nietzsche.

01:11:43.360 --> 01:11:45.540
This is all the life affirmation stuff.

01:11:46.060 --> 01:11:50.000
So, like, I've been so dissociated from the nihilist Nietzsche.

01:11:50.300 --> 01:12:01.800
And I don't know Batai's Nietzsche, but I do know that that, I mean, I don't know if this is what you're getting at, Nate, but that notion of sort of, like, he's of a great spirit that sort of overcame all of these other things.

01:12:01.800 --> 01:12:06.140
And he had all the excuses, but he was the great soul that overpowered all of it.

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:15.760
I increasingly am suspicious or sort of, like, I distance myself from that version of Nietzsche as well.

01:12:15.880 --> 01:12:27.720
Just because it doesn't seem like he's, like, you know, I think it's not my favorite way of thinking about, say, something like the will to power of, like, you know, I am, I'm going to dominate the things around me.

01:12:27.820 --> 01:12:29.360
I'm going to be self-controlled.

01:12:29.520 --> 01:12:33.480
I'm going to be the sovereign that's able to transcend my, I'm going to be the great man.

01:12:33.620 --> 01:12:34.600
I'm going to be the Übermensch.

01:12:34.780 --> 01:12:37.540
And that notion of the Übermensch.

01:12:37.540 --> 01:12:43.140
And, you know, the nature of affirmation is, like, I will be transformed.

01:12:43.320 --> 01:12:53.320
What looks like a terrible health, which is a terrible health for certain kinds of life, I shall affirm to become a great health for a very different kind.

01:12:53.480 --> 01:12:55.320
This is my health, not my sickness.

01:12:55.620 --> 01:12:55.960
It's my health.

01:12:55.960 --> 01:12:56.640
No, yes.

01:12:57.140 --> 01:13:06.680
I mean, I think that's what I was trying to say is that instead of devolving into the disposition that he critiques, he had all the excuses in order to lapse into that.

01:13:06.680 --> 01:13:10.160
And instead of that, he chose life affirmation, affirmation of difference.

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:11.260
And at the same time.

01:13:11.260 --> 01:13:14.020
Which is an impossible disposition at that time.

01:13:14.020 --> 01:13:24.480
Think about making, how do you reach out of your own era in order to sort of establish that kind of disorientation that basically he has, you know?

01:13:24.540 --> 01:13:25.580
Because it's not an orientation.

01:13:25.980 --> 01:13:27.960
It is an anti-orientation.

01:13:28.140 --> 01:13:35.820
I do sometimes think, though, that his writing to a posthumous audience is a major thing that allowed him to go forward.

01:13:35.820 --> 01:13:36.700
Gave him a review.

01:13:36.820 --> 01:13:39.180
He's like, these fucking idiots cannot hear me.

01:13:39.240 --> 01:13:44.660
The only way that I'm going to be able to do this thing is imagine a future reader that can hear me.

01:13:45.060 --> 01:13:47.260
I think that's a really good point.

01:13:47.440 --> 01:13:56.280
Writing to the future as a constitutive element of the philosophy, not a secondary rhetorical element in its usual sense.

01:13:56.920 --> 01:13:59.980
Yeah, or just even a pragmatics of the writing as well.

01:14:00.200 --> 01:14:03.840
That's how he, like, that's how, one of the ways he affirmed his, his life.

01:14:03.840 --> 01:14:04.440
That's cool.

01:14:04.580 --> 01:14:06.060
I want to try, I want to try that now.

01:14:06.120 --> 01:14:12.800
I wonder, like, I wonder if I think of my writing that way, if that's going to, I mean, that's, that's an interesting thought experiment.

01:14:12.800 --> 01:14:14.520
